                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="typednotes">
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_transcrSource" type="transcrSource">
                    	    
<p xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">Original manuscript</p>
                    	</note>
                    
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_dating" type="dating">
                    	    
<p xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">Gauguin thanks Van Gogh for his reply to <ref target="let581.xml">letter 581</ref> of about 29 February 1888. Cooper dated the present letter to about 19 March 1888; Merlhès to about 14-16 March; but neither put forward any arguments for this. In any event the letter dates from before about 21 March since this is when Vincent sent it on to Theo, enclosed with <ref target="let588.xml">letter 588</ref>. Since Gauguin complains of the ‘continual wind and rain’ <ref target="#l-19">(l. 19)</ref> and the wind began to strengthen in the west in the evening of the 16th, we have dated the letter between about Saturday, 17 and about Monday, 19 March 1888. See <hi rend="italics">Gauguin lettres</hi> 1983, p. 209, <hi rend="italics">Correspondance Gauguin</hi> 1984, p. 174 and <hi rend="italics">Météo-France</hi>.</p>
                    	</note>
                    
                    
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_remarks" type="remarks">
                    	    
                                    
<p xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">The letter was sent on to Theo with <ref target="let588.xml">letter 588</ref>.</p>
                                    
                                
                    	</note>
                    
                </listAnnotation>
