<p xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">Gauguin’s illness <ref target="let581.xml">(581)</ref></p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="notes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            

<p>This letter – Van Gogh’s reply to <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1039">Gauguin</rs>’s <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let581.xml">letter 581</ref> – has not survived.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="2" xml:id="note-t-2">
                            

<p>Vincent had urged Theo to do his best to sell <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1039">Gauguin</rs>’s work, and had given <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1334">Russell</rs> and Gauguin each other’s addresses in the hope that Russell might buy a painting from Gauguin. <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let582.xml">See letter 582</ref> and <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let583.xml">583</ref>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
